I did a Patreon end-of-year livestream last night.

My manager Zack chose 20 songs, mine and other people’s, and asked the patrons to vote on them.

He then sent me 15 random numbers, which I cut up and put in a hat, then pulled in real time, and performed - for an hour and thirty minutes. 

This was the second to last number pulled.

Happy new year!

Last weekend, I stood onstage in two small clubs in Brooklyn and I moved around a little and talked nonsense and played guitar and sang songs.

(I’ve been doing a version of this since May 1994, when I was 14 and my then-band Delusion, which later became Miracle of 86, played a club called The Rock Palace on Staten Island.)

These particular two shows were ostensibly retrospectives acknowledging 20ish years - give or take - of performing & releasing music under my own name.

I think I both basically understand the particular value of what I do while also frequently struggling to see the value in what I do.

Most of that has to do with internalizing culturally pervasive/perverse/condemning external metrics of success and the inevitable compare-and-despair we navigate as spiritual creatures having physical experiences in a material world. 

It’s a jungle out there, and in here.

The truth is, nobody deserves anything, and I have and have had so much, and whatever I don’t isn’t really my business, and it’s a ridiculous gift and honor to do any of this at any level, let alone to have people pay any sort of attention to it in a public-facing/gainful employment sort of way, for twentyish minutes, let alone twentyish years.

It would be a life beyond wildest dreams if that holds, even as it inevitably shifts, wildly and non-linearly. 

It already is.

Thank you for everything so far and for today.

See you at MSG for the 40th anniversary/retirement party.

Love,
Kevin

(I also meant to add a slide mentioning how lucky I’ve been to be a member of Miracle of 86 & Bad Books & Kenny O’Brien and The O’Douls and to have been invited to be a touring member of Brand New, The Front Bottoms, and Rachael Yamagata’s band at times in the past 20 years. I forgot to make the note. If I forgot anyone or anything else in the following slides, I’m sorry.)

I lived on Staten Island from the middle of 6th grade through the start of college, seven mega-formative years. 

My mom is still there, as are some of my best friends.

I’m very much from SI as much as I’m from Brooklyn, even if I’ve lived in Brooklyn nearly five times as long.

The punk/hardcore/DIY independent music scene on SI in the mid-90s was a pretty remarkable and singular godsend of an eye-level space that instructed & still animates how I approach making music & community.

I don’t get to play there very often; I do this Saturday, July 8th, for the MakerPark Radio 6th Anniversary Festival, with a bunch of other great bands. 

Music starts at 6pm, I play at 9:30.

You can get tickets at the door or via kevindevine.net/tour.

Justin Borucki took this picture of Miracle of 86 at the Joint on SI in … 1997, I bet?

Thanks,
Kevin
